 <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 916<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/29/02 10:53:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Project Orion: The True Story of the Atomic Ship</span><hr size=1> Imagine a spaceship 135 feet in diameter, and 10 stories tall. Imagine it weighing 4000 tons. Bet that doesn't sound too impressive. If this were a normal chemical rocket, only about 10 tons of this would make it into space. Now just imagine for a moment that there was a way to allow over 3500 tons of this ship to make it to orbit. This is possible, if a ship were to launch nuclear bombs as fuel. This is known as Project Orion <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com/b_projectorion.htm">Full Review</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 65<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/29/02 8:28:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Project Orion: The True Story of the Atomic Ship</span><hr size=1> It such a damn shame that we have this awesome power at our disposal but aren't allowed to use it.  Why does all the good stuff always have to be so forbidden? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/udustyslaunchpad.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/14/02 8:07:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Orion</span><hr size=1> Its worse than that!<br>
<br>
For good engineering reasons Orion is the the *only* way of getting large payloads (1000 tons upwards) into orbit.<br>
<br>
Unless Orion is developed we will *never* be able to put the hundreds of thousands of tons in orbit that will be nececary to colonise the solar system. <br>
<br>
using chemical rockets would be like the pilgrim fathers attempting to colonise america by crossing the atlantic one at a time in rowing boats.<br>
<br>
Dusty <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1018<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/14/02 8:42:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Orion</span><hr size=1> I agree with some reservations.  I would support a large scale test program.  An underground facility could be constructed to test various pusher plate designs with 'live' engine firing, advanced computer modelling could refine the design, build ONE big super Orion, capable of placing the industry in space to build additional Orions.  Call it a day, cause it's Miller Time! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/udrcarstairs.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 105<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/14/02 8:42:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.imgstudio.com/2002/March/28/stamp_lthumb/032820021216063.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  A step closer</span><hr size=1> I just picked up the October issue of <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://popularmechanics.com">Popular Mechanics</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, and there is an article of interest – Tiny Nukes!<br>
<br>
The website says that they will have articles from the October issue up in mid October!<br>
<br>
The idea has merit, but may ultimately fail thanks to the ever present nuclear phobia. Apparently Congress, in its microscopic wisdom, forbid the DOE from researching low-yield nuclear weapons in 1994 (they were afraid of “Suitcase Nukes”). Efforts to develop new low-yields will probably concentrate on using existing primary triggers from fusion devices.<br>
<br>
These purposed bunker-crackers are cool as all get out. They are looking into sheathing the missile with carbon-nanotube materials (Best would love this), which is “virtually” indestructible.<br>
<br>
Fallout may be a problem. One designer believes the fallout will be completely contained in the rock, while another says the blast will form a chimney of sorts and channel the material out and into the air. <br>
<br>
The design calls for a yield of around 0.1kt, a fraction of the Hiroshima blast. Tiny nukes are what is needed for Orion, and any step toward them is a step in the right direction.  <p><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"><p>
Dr. Carstairs<p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2054<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/15/02 4:13:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Let's do it.</span><hr size=1> On the plus side, the door is wide open for those enterprising enough to go it alone. All you need is billions of dollars, an independant nation with no nuclear treaty obligations and a secret location to develop your Orions.<br>
<br>
Piece of cake.<br>
<br>
Maybe a polar region Island as opposed to a tropical one as I previously put forward. We wont be able to work on our tans but there are certain advantages. We would be closer to the ideal launch site. No immediate neighbours. We would have a very good excuse to buy a reactor from Russia. Heating and electricity would be essential there. I don't think we would be setting any kind of precedent since Siberia and other cold places rely on it. Orion would have to operate in the coldness of space so subzero temperatures shouldnt be a hindrance to engineering. A nuclear power plant can supply the energy needs of a city in any case. So we shouldn't freeze. Best of all, the ships could be hidden in underground ice caverns. We just melt them out. Let's face it. The U.S isn't going to let somebody else take control of space if they catch wind of it. <br>
<br>
Still, a tropical Pacific Island from the Indonesian archipelago does have a better sound to it.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 105<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/15/02 5:30:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/pubimage.asp?id_=638250 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Project Orion: The True Story of the Atomic Ship</span><hr size=1> Security would probably be easier to maintain on a polar island as well since it would likely be out of the way of major air and sea lanes, particularly if it was near the Antartic.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2072<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/15/02 7:44:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Polar Nuclear Nation.</span><hr size=1> Exactly.<br>
<br>
Cheaper to buy aswell if you can find a seller. The poles are generally regarded as international territory I believe. The islands which exist there are generally considered uninhabitable. Only weather stations exist in a few remote spots. I daresay any group could set up shop and not even be noticed.<br>
In some countries you can squat in a house for a few years and then if nobody kicks you out during that time then you are legally able to claim the house. I wonder how it relates to land masses.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/16/02 8:02:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/pubimage.asp?id_=638250 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Project Orion: The True Story of the Atomic Ship</span><hr size=1> Not to long ago I was also thinking about the possibilities of finding a reclusive, uninhabited island somewhere and illegally setting up shop in a lowkey manner.  Assuming you could successfully setup a small research base on one of these islands, I wonder how you could go about getting the talent you need while at the same time keeping your activities secret from the authorities.  God forbid if we were to accidently haul someone like Yales over there.  We'd all be up on charges in the Hague!  Oh yeah, one more advantage to being close to the pole, we'd already be in the vicinity of our launching site!   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2090<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/16/02 11:29:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=136.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Secret Island.</span><hr size=1> We couldn't keep it secret long. Not unless we used freelance talent (unemployed and disgruntled). We simply advertise for the relevant positions I guess. Include a clause prohibiting departure from the island until completion of the project. <br>
<br>
It would take big bucks. You can't deal with the regular terrorist organisations to aquire Uranium. Those guys are being watched too hard. Perhaps India would sell you the plans for a Breeder reactor. You could then also save some money by hiring staff there. How they will get along with any Russians onboard I don't know. Probably ok. They both hate the US and China.<br>
<br>
Any number of nations will sell you missile technology which could be converted to space rocketry. Otherwise you could just build a factory and start from scratch. You might have to anyway.<br>
<br>
To avoid a hostile infiltration you ofcourse drug all potential employees during passage to the island. Before they go to sleep. Pump them full of truth serum and see what happens. If they are a spy, then you give them a job sweeping floors at a different island. Until they get sick of it and leave. These guys are scientists and engineers. Not professional infiltrators who have practiced for years developing an immunity to mind altering drugs.<br>
<br>
Either that or hire directly. Less risky than advertising. If you are trying to recruit a Russian then pretend to be a US government agent. For a US scientist, vice versa.<br>
